SIMPLE: maintenance
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Maintenance
<hw>Main"te*nance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>maintenance</ets>. See <er>Maintain</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of maintaining; sustenance; support; defense;
vindication.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whatsoever is granted to the church for God's honor and the
<qex>maintenance</qex> of his service, is granted to God.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which maintains or supports; means of
sustenance; supply of necessaries and conveniences.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Those of better fortune not making learning their
<qex>maintenance</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Crim. Law)</fld> <def>An officious or unlawful
intermeddling in a cause depending between others, by assisting either
party with money or means to carry it on. See <er>Champerty</er>.</def>
<rj><au>Wharton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Those actions required for the care of machinery, a
building, etc., to keep it clean and in proper functioning condition,
and to prevent or forestall damage due to normal use.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Payments, such as child support or alimony, to a
dependent child not living with one or to a divorced wife.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Cap of maintenance</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Cap</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>maintenance man</ent>⟦br⟧
